WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.350 --> 00:00:05.138
FEMALE SPEAKER: Please
welcome Dr. Temple Grandin.

00:00:05.138 --> 00:00:10.886
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:10.886 --> 00:00:13.340
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: It's
really great to be here today.

00:00:13.340 --> 00:00:15.780
I'm gonna talk about a
lot of different things.

00:00:15.780 --> 00:00:18.830
I was one of those kids that was
kind of different growing up,

00:00:18.830 --> 00:00:21.320
bullied and teased in school.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:24.020
And the thing that saved
me was my science teacher.

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:26.080
I had a great
science teacher that

00:00:26.080 --> 00:00:28.920
got me interested in doing all
kinds of interesting projects.

00:00:28.920 --> 00:00:31.265
Which brings it down to
you want to get kids doing

00:00:31.265 --> 00:00:32.890
interesting stuff,
you're going to have

00:00:32.890 --> 00:00:35.410
to show them interesting stuff.

00:00:35.410 --> 00:00:38.370
There's a scene in the HBO movie
where I got really interested

00:00:38.370 --> 00:00:40.740
in optical illusion rooms.

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:43.240
Well, and I actually saw
that optical illusion room

00:00:43.240 --> 00:00:46.600
on a Bell Labs 16
millimeter movie-- now

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:50.850
I'm showing how long ago that
was-- on optical illusions.

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:54.200
So you know, gotta get them
out there and show them stuff.

00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:56.430
Now the thing is,
what I want to do

00:00:56.430 --> 00:00:59.270
is to get you thinking about
different kinds of minds

00:00:59.270 --> 00:01:01.330
that think differently.

00:01:01.330 --> 00:01:04.599
When I was in 20s,
30s, and early 40s,

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:09.180
I thought that everybody thought
the same way that I think.

00:01:09.180 --> 00:01:11.040
Then I asked this
question, and this

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:14.110
is where I learned how
thinking can be different.

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:16.600
Access your memory
on a church steeple.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:19.990
How does that information
come into your mind?

00:01:19.990 --> 00:01:22.290
I was shocked to find
out that a lot of people

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:24.780
get this vague,
generalized thing.

00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:27.260
I don't have any vague
generalized thing.

00:01:27.260 --> 00:01:29.280
I only have specific ones.

00:01:29.280 --> 00:01:33.030
Now you might ask, why am I
talking about church steeples?

00:01:33.030 --> 00:01:35.340
Why don't I ask house or car?

00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:37.630
Well, most people are so
familiar with their own home

00:01:37.630 --> 00:01:41.020
or their own car, that
they're going to see that.

00:01:41.020 --> 00:01:43.570
But I wanted to ask you
something you don't own,

00:01:43.570 --> 00:01:46.010
but they're out there
and you have to see them

00:01:46.010 --> 00:01:49.474
and everybody knows
what they are.

00:01:49.474 --> 00:01:51.140
And you have to see
a whole lot of them.

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:53.150
You just can't even drive
around without seeing them.

00:01:53.150 --> 00:01:54.570
And that really
started giving me

00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:59.130
some real insight that different
people think differently.

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:02.430
So then I divided
the world into people

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.947
that think in words and
people that think in pictures.

00:02:04.947 --> 00:02:06.780
And then I started to--
well, wait a minute.

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:10.669
There's this other kind of
person that thinks in patterns.

00:02:10.669 --> 00:02:14.450
This is more the
mathematical kind of mind.

00:02:14.450 --> 00:02:18.895
Now when does something
become an abnormality?

00:02:18.895 --> 00:02:22.060
Well, you get a little
bit of the autism trait,

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:25.940
you take out some social
stuff in the brain,

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:30.076
and you get geek traits for
all kinds of fun tech stuff.

00:02:30.076 --> 00:02:32.450
I think a brain can either be
made more cognitive or more

00:02:32.450 --> 00:02:35.340
thinking, or a brain
can be made more social.

00:02:35.340 --> 00:02:38.492
Because after all, who
invented the first stone spear?

00:02:38.492 --> 00:02:42.460
It wasn't the yack-yacks around
the campfire, that's for sure.

00:02:42.460 --> 00:02:43.584
[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]

00:02:43.584 --> 00:02:45.500
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: It
was some geek out there

