I'll tell you, the
football players

00:11:59.870 --> 00:12:02.320
doesn't look very pretty.

00:12:05.810 --> 00:12:07.374
OK, now this is
another scan that

00:12:07.374 --> 00:12:08.790
was done at the
University of Utah

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:11.350
and presented at the
Neuroscience Meeting.

00:12:11.350 --> 00:12:15.130
And the blue part is basically
full of cerebrospinal fluid.

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:16.090
It's full of water.

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:19.730
And you can see, I've got
a big asymmetry there.

00:12:19.730 --> 00:12:23.130
I got visual thinking and my
math department got trashed.

00:12:23.130 --> 00:12:27.030
See, where I think innate
differences make the biggest

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:30.400
difference is either in
real deficit in something

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:32.990
or an extreme
ability in something.

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:34.910
Yes, there's brain plasticity.

00:12:34.910 --> 00:12:38.060
But that's happening in the
gray matter out on the edges.

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:39.730
Those big white fiber
bundles, I don't

00:12:39.730 --> 00:12:41.400
think you grow those
big axons back.

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:43.520
I mean, they're that long.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:47.640
OK Malcolm Gladwell says
if you have enough practice

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:49.500
and you have enough
access to services,

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:50.820
anyone can learn anything.

00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:53.510
Well, back in '68,
Bill Gates and I

00:12:53.510 --> 00:12:57.390
had access to this exact
same computer system.

00:12:57.390 --> 00:13:00.650
I wanted to learn how to program
it, it was just hopeless.

00:13:00.650 --> 00:13:03.440
Algebra, just hopeless.

00:13:03.440 --> 00:13:06.150
I wanted to become
an expert skier.

00:13:06.150 --> 00:13:08.199
I could never keep
them together.

00:13:08.199 --> 00:13:09.990
I could get to the good
intermediate stage.

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:11.720
I mean, I could
ski recreationally.

00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:13.230
But get really good?

00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:17.446
There were other kids, one
winter they'd be experts.

00:13:17.446 --> 00:13:19.560
Well, I just couldn't
do computer programming,

00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:21.220
no matter how hard I tried.

00:13:21.220 --> 00:13:24.410
I agree with Gladwell about
the practice, and of course,

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:28.790
the access to the teaching.

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:31.410
You know, you have
to develop abilities.

00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:35.630
This is probably one of
my most important slides.

00:13:35.630 --> 00:13:39.250
The different kinds
of minds slide.

00:13:39.250 --> 00:13:42.600
I am a photo-realistic
visual thinker.

00:13:42.600 --> 00:13:45.590
An object visualizer.

00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:48.650
Lot of people in programming
are a pattern visualizer,

00:13:48.650 --> 00:13:50.170
a spatial visualizer.

00:13:50.170 --> 00:13:54.740
See, in your brain you have
circuits for what is something?

00:13:54.740 --> 00:13:56.150
That's me.

00:13:56.150 --> 00:13:59.244
And then you got circuits
for where is something?

00:13:59.244 --> 00:14:01.035
And people that are
super good at the where

00:14:01.035 --> 00:14:04.030
is something located
in space tend

00:14:04.030 --> 00:14:07.880
to not be so good at the
object visualization.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:11.430
And the pattern thinkers
are also often good at math.

00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:13.260
These kids often have
trouble with reading.

00:14:13.260 --> 00:14:15.857
I hear stories where OK, they're
having handwriting problems

00:14:15.857 --> 00:14:17.440
and they won't let
them type a laptop.

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:19.000
That's just stupid.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:20.700
Another thing that
I hear that's really

00:14:20.700 --> 00:14:23.080
bad-- political
correctness gone crazy--

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.437
is you've got a fourth
grader bored doing baby math.

00:14:27.437 --> 00:14:29.770
And they make them do baby
math and they don't give them

00:14:29.770 --> 00:14:31.270
the more advanced book.

00:14:31.270 --> 00:14:32.680
That's just ridiculous.

00:14:32.680 --> 00:14:34.600
You can get into
a situation where

00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:38.660
a kid may be gifted in math
but need special ed in reading.

00:14:38.660 --> 00:14:41.630
Now I like to bust
out of the silos.

00:14:41.630 --> 00:14:44.010
Everybody tends to get
inside their own box.

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:45.980
There's a text box.

00:14:45.980 --> 00:14:48.480
There's a farm and ranch box.

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:50.430
There's a gifted box.

00:14:50.430 --> 00:14:53.940
And there's an
autism box or silos.

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:56.554
And I like to pick out
my speaking engagements

00:14:56.554 --> 00:14:58.220
so I like to get a
little mixture of all

00:14:58.220 --> 00:15:00.030
these different things.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:02.750
Because I'm seeing something
that kind of disturbs me.

00:15:02.750 --> 00:15:05.880
I go to an autism meeting and
a geeky little 10 year-old

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:08.200
walks up to me, a real
smart little 10 year-old,

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:11.300
and he's fixated on his autism.

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:13.789
And sometimes they get kind
of a handicap mentality

00:15:13.789 --> 00:15:15.330
and they're not
learning basic stuff,

00:15:15.330 --> 00:15:16.950
like saying please
and thank you.

00:15:16.950 --> 00:15:19.100
Learning just basic skills.

00:15:19.100 --> 00:15:20.620
Kind of get over protected.

00:15:20.620 --> 00:15:22.240
Then I go to a gifted meeting.

00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:24.955
The same little geeky
kid comes up to me,

00:15:24.955 --> 00:15:27.330
but he wants to tell me about
what he saw under the Brock

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:30.070
Magiscope, which is a really
cool little children's

00:15:30.070 --> 00:15:31.520
microscope.

00:15:31.520 --> 00:15:34.220
And then I go to
a place like this,

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:37.381
all full of undiagnosed
little bit on the spectrum.

00:15:37.381 --> 00:15:39.786
[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]

00:15:39.786 --> 00:15:42.890
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: Avoid
the labels like the plague,

00:15:42.890 --> 00:15:44.910
'cause it might hold you back.

00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:48.220
Now where learning about autism
can really help some of you

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:51.670
guys here is in
your relationships.

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:54.230
You don't need to go
out and get diagnosed,

00:15:54.230 --> 00:15:56.671
but just reading about
it, that can help you out.

00:15:56.671 --> 00:15:59.170
And then I go over to the farm
and ranch and the meat world,

00:15:59.170 --> 00:16:01.480
and I go to this big
huge meatpacking plant.

00:16:01.480 --> 00:16:03.450
And there's this old
gray haired hippie

00:16:03.450 --> 00:16:05.390
and he runs the
maintenance shop.

00:16:05.390 --> 00:16:08.065
And he's out there playing
with the giant LEGOs putting up

00:16:08.065 --> 00:16:09.220
a new cooler.

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:12.610
Big huge concrete LEGOs, you
use a crane to put them up.

00:16:12.610 --> 00:16:16.999
And he's pure spectrum, but
he had welding in high school.

00:16:16.999 --> 00:16:19.040
The worst things they've
done in the high schools

00:16:19.040 --> 00:16:22.100
is taken the hands-on classes.

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:25.430
In fact, at JPL they make all
the metal parts of something

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:28.570
like the Mars lander, they
make them there in shops.

00:16:28.570 --> 00:16:31.070
And they're having
problems finding

00:16:31.070 --> 00:16:33.880
who's going to replace the
machinists when they retire.

00:16:33.880 --> 00:16:36.454
Now a third kind of thinker
is the verbal facts thinker.

00:16:36.454 --> 00:16:38.870
They know everything about
whatever their favorite subject

00:16:38.870 --> 00:16:40.610
is and they're a verbal thinker.

00:16:40.610 --> 00:16:42.320
Now so-called
normal people, they

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:46.810
are mixtures of these
different kinds of thinking.

00:16:46.810 --> 00:16:48.959
But I'm finding, when you
get into autism programs,

00:16:48.959 --> 00:16:50.375
there's an awful
lot of smart kids

00:16:50.375 --> 00:16:54.310
that ought to get headed down
a track towards Google or JPL,

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:56.460
that the teachers
and the schools

00:16:56.460 --> 00:16:58.155
are having a hard
time shifting gears

00:16:58.155 --> 00:17:00.245
on how to deal with
the nonverbal kids

00:17:00.245 --> 00:17:03.360
and they got smart, geeky,
kids in that same class.

00:17:03.360 --> 00:17:07.130
It's a really,
really big problem.

00:17:07.130 --> 00:17:09.180
Because I can think of
kids I went to school

00:17:09.180 --> 00:17:11.210
with when I was
in college that I

00:17:11.210 --> 00:17:13.160
know are on the spectrum today.

00:17:13.160 --> 00:17:15.560
But the problem that the
parents of little kids

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:18.190
have and the schools have,
in order to get a service,

00:17:18.190 --> 00:17:19.430
you have to have a label.

00:17:19.430 --> 00:17:21.430
Now I don't think it hurts
a kid when he's three

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.180
to put a label on him
to get speech therapy.

00:17:24.180 --> 00:17:27.230
But then you get the kid that's
10 or 12 years old getting

00:17:27.230 --> 00:17:29.070
bullied in school,
and he gets a label

00:17:29.070 --> 00:17:31.547
because you get
bullied in school.

00:17:31.547 --> 00:17:33.505
And Steve Jobs was one
of the kids with-- well,

00:17:33.505 --> 00:17:35.130
they had to take him
out of one school,

00:17:35.130 --> 00:17:37.480
put him in another
school in Cupertino.

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:41.095
And fortunately, he had a
dad that had a machine shop.

00:17:41.095 --> 00:17:44.790
That was another thing
that was his salvation.

00:17:44.790 --> 00:17:48.080
He was doing hands-on things.

00:17:48.080 --> 00:17:49.744
Now I know that
Steve Jobs may not

00:17:49.744 --> 00:17:51.410
be the best thing to
be mentioning here.

00:17:51.410 --> 00:17:53.540
But I only can talk
about the dead ones

00:17:53.540 --> 00:17:55.800
where I have information
I've gotten off

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:58.580
of publicly available things
like books and "Business Week"

00:17:58.580 --> 00:18:01.730
magazine, which
I've read carefully.

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:05.250
Now in "The Autistic
Brain" book,

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:08.190
I now show evidence that
these two kinds of visualizers

00:18:08.190 --> 00:18:10.510
actually do exist.

00:18:10.510 --> 00:18:13.490
Today the schools are
all about evidence based.

00:18:13.490 --> 00:18:15.640
Well, Marie Kozhevnikof's work.

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:17.890
Surfing the internet, three
o'clock in the morning, I,

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:20.790
found her stuff about the
two kinds of visualizers.

00:18:20.790 --> 00:18:25.030
This PET brain scan
study show that these two

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:26.190
kinds of visualizers exist.

00:18:26.190 --> 00:18:28.190
I was so happy
when I found this.

00:18:28.190 --> 00:18:31.340
Because I had just observed
these things just on my own.

00:18:31.340 --> 00:18:34.060
And when I did my TED talk, I
hadn't found these references

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:34.560
yet.

00:18:34.560 --> 00:18:37.030
And they weren't
very easy to find.

00:18:37.030 --> 00:18:40.800
There's kind of a bias
about innate ability.

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:42.640
No, everyone's not the same.

00:18:42.640 --> 00:18:44.120
Yes, there's a
lot of plasticity.

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:46.529
You got a lot of people
here in the middle.

00:18:46.529 --> 00:18:48.320
You can get them pretty
good at programming

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:49.810
up to here or whatever,
but you probably

00:18:49.810 --> 00:18:50.700
won't get them to here.

00:18:50.700 --> 00:18:52.491
They can move back and
forth in the middle.

00:18:52.491 --> 00:18:54.320
That gray matter's got
a lot of plasticity.

00:18:54.320 --> 00:18:57.470
But then you've got these great
big huge white matter cables.

00:18:57.470 --> 00:19:00.760
Well, you're kind of
born with those things.

00:19:00.760 --> 00:19:02.600
OK, there's two ways
you can do the math.

00:19:02.600 --> 00:19:04.100
You can do it the
verbal way, or you

00:19:04.100 --> 00:19:05.683
can do it the more
visual spatial way.

00:19:05.683 --> 00:19:08.130
And there's kids that can just
do the math in their head.

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:10.600
And the school says
well, you can't do that.

00:19:10.600 --> 00:19:12.860
They don't get it that
he thinks differently.

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:15.530
Well, I'm saying let
him do it in his head.

00:19:15.530 --> 00:19:19.417
But we will take some
precautions against cheating.

00:19:19.417 --> 00:19:21.250
So we're going to put
him in a room stripped

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:23.650
of everything electronic, and
if he can do it, then just

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:25.799
absolutely fine.

00:19:25.799 --> 00:19:27.340
Now I just want to
show you something

00:19:27.340 --> 00:19:29.840
that's definitely not my mind.

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:33.950
That praying mantis is
made out of a single sheet

00:19:33.950 --> 00:19:35.730
of folded paper.

00:19:35.730 --> 00:19:37.225
No cutting, no tape.

00:19:37.225 --> 00:19:39.530
And what you see
in the background,

00:19:39.530 --> 00:19:42.170
that is the folding pattern.

00:19:42.170 --> 00:19:45.150
And people look at
that and go, wow.

00:19:45.150 --> 00:19:47.220
Well, there's no
way I could start

00:19:47.220 --> 00:19:50.700
with a square piece of paper and
make it into a praying mantis.

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:52.160
That's not my mind.

00:19:52.160 --> 00:19:53.840
And here are some
great little origami

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:55.915
stars that some kids gave me.

00:19:55.915 --> 00:19:58.950
Well, they need to be in
the advanced math class.

00:19:58.950 --> 00:20:00.870
Now my thing was art.

00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:04.150
And when I was in elementary
school, my ability in art

00:20:04.150 --> 00:20:05.324
was always encouraged.

00:20:05.324 --> 00:20:07.490
And I was encouraged to do
lots of different things.

00:20:07.490 --> 00:20:10.200
So I wasn't just
drawing the same horse

00:20:10.200 --> 00:20:11.640
head over and over again.

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:13.480
You gotta take the
things they're fixated on

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:15.090
and broaden it
out, 'cause you've

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:19.100
got to learn how to do stuff
other people are going to want.

00:20:19.100 --> 00:20:22.640
I always like to show
my drawings off again.

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:26.560
And here's a beautiful
bridge that Jessy Park drew.

00:20:26.560 --> 00:20:27.870
She was more moderate.

00:20:27.870 --> 00:20:30.720
Well, her favorite thing used
to be electric blanket controls.

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.662
Well, we had to get
her off of that.

00:20:33.662 --> 00:20:36.740
And while on the
subject of bridges,

00:20:36.740 --> 00:20:39.660
I think our governments
are going crazy

00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:44.590
when you've got a governor
and his aides are deliberately

00:20:44.590 --> 00:20:47.170
creating traffic
jams on a bridge!

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:48.630
The one that looks
just like this.

00:20:48.630 --> 00:20:52.360
This is absolutely ridiculous!

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:57.080
They're getting totally
separated from reality.

00:20:57.080 --> 00:20:59.729
We have great things going
on with private industry

00:20:59.729 --> 00:21:01.020
docking with the space station.

00:21:01.020 --> 00:21:02.510
But instead we
have a stupid thing

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:06.210
on the news this morning
about government officials

00:21:06.210 --> 00:21:08.600
messing up traffic on
purpose on a bridge,

00:21:08.600 --> 00:21:12.770
and some dumb thing about
I think sports players

00:21:12.770 --> 00:21:15.410
getting scared by
their own mascot.

00:21:15.410 --> 00:21:18.960
I mean, that was on
the news this morning

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:21.529
when I was having breakfast.

00:21:21.529 --> 00:21:23.070
I think there's more
important things

00:21:23.070 --> 00:21:24.740
to have on the news than that.

00:21:24.740 --> 00:21:26.920
And these people, as far
as causing a traffic jam

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:29.125
on a bridge, that's
the kind of mindset

00:21:29.125 --> 00:21:31.700
of about an eight year-old.

00:21:31.700 --> 00:21:35.077
It's also something that
I would have learned

00:21:35.077 --> 00:21:37.160
when I was eight years old
that you don't do stuff

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:39.575
like that because it
inconveniences other people.

00:21:39.575 --> 00:21:41.150
You don't do those
kind of things

00:21:41.150 --> 00:21:43.565
'cause you wouldn't like if
you were in that traffic jam.

00:21:43.565 --> 00:21:45.650
It's just that simple.

00:21:45.650 --> 00:21:47.600
There's some other
gorgeous artwork

00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:50.950
made by a person that was
at mid-level on their autism

00:21:50.950 --> 00:21:52.110
spectrum.

00:21:52.110 --> 00:21:53.720
All right, now
I'm gonna tell you

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:57.560
math people why you need
to have us art minds.

00:21:57.560 --> 00:22:04.789
One of the things that really
worries me, with all the STEM

00:22:04.789 --> 00:22:07.080
emphasis-- and we're going
to have to have algebra now.

00:22:07.080 --> 00:22:08.220
How could I get through
college with algebra?

00:22:08.220 --> 00:22:09.910
Know how I got through college?

00:22:09.910 --> 00:22:14.510
Because thank goodness for
the educational fads of 1967.

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:19.760
And in 1967, the required
math class was finite math.

00:22:19.760 --> 00:22:22.050
Probability, matrices,
and statistics.

00:22:22.050 --> 00:22:24.300
Bit more visual,
tons of tutoring.

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:26.720
I managed to get through it.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:29.094
But the engineering mind
does need the art mind.

00:22:29.094 --> 00:22:31.510
'Cause I've learned there's
certain things the engineering

00:22:31.510 --> 00:22:33.065
mind doesn't see.

00:22:33.065 --> 00:22:34.930
Now what's there?

00:22:34.930 --> 00:22:38.140
I don't know if that came
from-- I got a satellite image.

00:22:38.140 --> 00:22:40.127
I don't know if it's
Google's or not.

00:22:40.127 --> 00:22:41.460
I did get that off the internet.

00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:43.293
I certainly wasn't gonna
fly over it and get

00:22:43.293 --> 00:22:48.090
my own picture of the
Fukushima nuclear power plant.

00:22:48.090 --> 00:22:51.270
Not something you want
to get very, very near,

00:22:51.270 --> 00:22:53.370
that's for sure.

00:22:53.370 --> 00:22:57.230
'Cause sometimes the most
obvious is the least obvious.

00:22:57.230 --> 00:22:59.722
So I was getting all these
newspapers, all this stuff,

00:22:59.722 --> 00:23:01.305
and reading about
it on a plane 'cause

00:23:01.305 --> 00:23:02.120
I find this stuff interesting.

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:03.840
And when I found out
why this happened,

00:23:03.840 --> 00:23:06.620
I'm going how could you do this?

00:23:06.620 --> 00:23:10.745
I can't design a nuclear
reactor, there's no way.

00:23:10.745 --> 00:23:13.120
But if I had been drawing the
concrete work for the plant

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:15.300
and doing my site
elevation drawings,

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:18.200
there's no way I would have
made a mistake they made.

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:20.540
All I have to know
about a nuclear reactor

00:23:20.540 --> 00:23:23.195
is if the emergency pump fails
to work after you've scrammed

00:23:23.195 --> 00:23:27.380
it-- see it doesn't quite get
turned off all the way-- it

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:29.980
burns up and you're in so
much trouble it's not funny.

