00:35:05.380 --> 00:35:07.260
and told them to
move their trailers.

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:10.010
But once they got established,
then you're just stuck with it.

00:35:10.010 --> 00:35:12.176
Did they ask permission to
put those trailers there?

00:35:12.176 --> 00:35:15.450
I'm sure they did not.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:17.650
OK, airport category.

00:35:17.650 --> 00:35:21.390
Now when you think about
really big amounts of money,

00:35:21.390 --> 00:35:23.990
let's start thinking
about it in something

00:35:23.990 --> 00:35:25.660
the public can understand.

00:35:25.660 --> 00:35:27.529
This is worth $5 billion.

00:35:27.529 --> 00:35:29.820
And they're building a new
light rail and a new Westin.

00:35:29.820 --> 00:35:31.360
I gotta get the price
for that 'cause that's

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:33.210
going to be quite a lot
more than $5 billion

00:35:33.210 --> 00:35:34.532
when that's done.

00:35:34.532 --> 00:35:35.990
But if we start
thinking about some

00:35:35.990 --> 00:35:39.030
of these big amounts of money
in something real like airport

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:45.030
units, then people can
really put it in perspective.

00:35:45.030 --> 00:35:49.070
So you got Denver Airport,
Dallas-Fort Worth, Minneapolis,

00:35:49.070 --> 00:35:50.570
Atlanta.

00:35:50.570 --> 00:35:55.250
And you've got the grungy
old terminal at LaGuardia.

00:35:55.250 --> 00:35:59.030
And it'd be fun to
explore that place.

00:35:59.030 --> 00:36:01.460
And when I asked an
astrophysicist about the church

00:36:01.460 --> 00:36:04.480
steeples, he saw a motion of
people singing and praying.

00:36:04.480 --> 00:36:05.980
I go, oh wow.

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:07.140
Trippy.

00:36:07.140 --> 00:36:11.010
That is definitely not my mind.

00:36:11.010 --> 00:36:13.070
Now cattle will make a category.

00:36:13.070 --> 00:36:16.410
If they get used to being
handled by a man on a horse,

00:36:16.410 --> 00:36:18.050
they've learned that's safe.

00:36:18.050 --> 00:36:20.910
The first time they see the
man on the ground, they panic.

00:36:20.910 --> 00:36:21.910
You see, it's different.

00:36:21.910 --> 00:36:23.030
It's a different picture.

00:36:23.030 --> 00:36:25.280
I've learned man on
the horse is safe.

00:36:25.280 --> 00:36:27.340
Man on the ground's
new and scary.

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:32.102
I can also learn that man
on the ground is safe.

00:36:32.102 --> 00:36:33.560
But that's something
totally novel.

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:35.935
You see, most people wouldn't
think the man on the ground

00:36:35.935 --> 00:36:37.410
is something novel.

00:36:37.410 --> 00:36:40.920
Now I find when you're trying
to categorize problems,

00:36:40.920 --> 00:36:42.830
a lot of people have
trouble categorizing

00:36:42.830 --> 00:36:44.470
where's a problem coming from?

00:36:44.470 --> 00:36:46.700
OK, if I got something
wrong in a factory,

00:36:46.700 --> 00:36:49.850
is there's something wrong
with the equipment or something

00:36:49.850 --> 00:36:54.160
wrong with how people are
operating that equipment?

00:36:54.160 --> 00:36:57.550
I find people often don't
make that differentiation.

00:36:57.550 --> 00:36:59.720
If it's equipment
problem, is it a glitch?

00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:02.053
Course with the meat plant--
and I've done a lot of work

00:37:02.053 --> 00:37:03.110
with them- stuck trolley.

00:37:03.110 --> 00:37:06.310
Or is it a fundamental
design problem?

00:37:06.310 --> 00:37:08.550
They don't make that
differentiation.

00:37:08.550 --> 00:37:10.480
I've got a problem
with a kid in school.

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:12.730
Does he have a
biological problem?

00:37:12.730 --> 00:37:15.440
Maybe his tummy hurts so much
that he can't pay attention

00:37:15.440 --> 00:37:16.570
in school.

00:37:16.570 --> 00:37:19.130
Or does he just not
want to do the work?

00:37:19.130 --> 00:37:21.320
It's just strictly behavior?

00:37:21.320 --> 00:37:26.640
Top down thinkers tend to
overgeneralize, especially

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:30.630
when they're not doing
practical things anymore.

00:37:30.630 --> 00:37:35.860
Well, I got this out of
one of the tech magazines

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:36.970
about dog fooding.

00:37:36.970 --> 00:37:40.320
You know, you gotta use
the stuff that you make.

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:44.070
Then you really find out
if it actually works.

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:46.300
Policymakers need to
be directly experience

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:48.260
the consequences
of their policies.

00:37:48.260 --> 00:37:50.510
And if you want to mess up
traffic and cause a traffic

00:37:50.510 --> 00:37:52.884
jam, then you need to be stuck
in the middle of the worst

00:37:52.884 --> 00:37:54.430
traffic jam.

00:37:54.430 --> 00:37:56.585
Well, there are
the guys up at JPL.

00:37:56.585 --> 00:37:58.450
It was very cool to
get to meet them.

00:38:01.470 --> 00:38:03.590
You know, kind of
unconventional.

00:38:03.590 --> 00:38:05.673
It's OK to be eccentric.

00:38:05.673 --> 00:38:06.173
That's OK.

00:38:06.173 --> 00:38:09.880
Some of the most creative people
are really, really eccentric

00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:12.570
and they're doing
marvelous things.

00:38:12.570 --> 00:38:14.150
And in talking to
the public, we need

00:38:14.150 --> 00:38:17.300
to tell the public well,
what are some of the spin

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:19.360
offs from maybe some
of the JPL stuff?

00:38:19.360 --> 00:38:20.750
Not stuff from the '60s.

00:38:20.750 --> 00:38:22.090
That's ancient history.

00:38:22.090 --> 00:38:25.010
Let's look at inventions
in the last 10 or 15 years.

00:38:25.010 --> 00:38:28.320
How about the
active pixel sensor?

00:38:28.320 --> 00:38:31.050
That's the heart of
the cell phone camera.

00:38:31.050 --> 00:38:33.370
How about coding
that's involved that

00:38:33.370 --> 00:38:37.080
will help the phone to work
from one cell phone tower

00:38:37.080 --> 00:38:38.710
to another cell phone tower?

00:38:38.710 --> 00:38:41.670
How about a mass
spectrometer this big?

00:38:41.670 --> 00:38:45.780
Yeah, we have mass spectrometers
the size of a giant desk.

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:47.382
Well, you can put
a sample in that

00:38:47.382 --> 00:38:49.090
and it'll tell you
what chemical's in it.

00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:52.460
Well that would have a lot
of really good useful uses.

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:55.320
Well, I was more interested in
looking at pictures of things

00:38:55.320 --> 00:38:56.320
than pictures of people.

00:38:56.320 --> 00:38:58.701
But we need people
interested in things.

00:38:58.701 --> 00:39:00.200
'Cause the social
yakity-yaks aren't

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:01.949
going to solve some
of the energy problems

00:39:01.949 --> 00:39:04.400
and stuff like that.

00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:06.410
Let's have some of the
kids that are different.

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:09.140
I don't care if
they're labeled gifted,

00:39:09.140 --> 00:39:14.806
they're labeled quirky,
weird, nerds, or mild autism.

00:39:14.806 --> 00:39:17.180
One thing you gotta do with
these kids when they're young

00:39:17.180 --> 00:39:20.710
is you gotta stretch them just
outside their comfort zone.

00:39:20.710 --> 00:39:25.110
And the other thing is we need
to be learning job skills.

00:39:25.110 --> 00:39:27.150
That needs to start at age 12.

00:39:27.150 --> 00:39:29.380
We need to find paper
route substitutes.

00:39:29.380 --> 00:39:31.520
Things like walking
dogs for the neighbors,

00:39:31.520 --> 00:39:34.240
things like maybe setting
up chairs at the community

00:39:34.240 --> 00:39:35.820
center, something like that.

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:39.360
One place where all my teachers
and everybody drew a line,

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:42.590
I wasn't allowed to become
a recluse in my room.

00:39:42.590 --> 00:39:45.050
That was absolutely not allowed.

00:39:45.050 --> 00:39:48.810
I had to get out and do things.

00:39:48.810 --> 00:39:50.980
Kids aren't doing
free play, which

00:39:50.980 --> 00:39:53.130
teaches valuable social skills.

00:39:53.130 --> 00:39:55.570
You know, dogs need to do
this too when they're young.

00:39:55.570 --> 00:39:57.650
Because if dogs don't do
this when they're young,

00:39:57.650 --> 00:39:59.847
then they fight other dogs
really viciously 'cause

00:39:59.847 --> 00:40:03.160
they never learned
how to get along.

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:05.580
Taking out the hands-on
classes was the worst thing

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:06.660
the schools ever did.

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:10.480
They took out cooking, sewing,
woodworking, machine shop,

00:40:10.480 --> 00:40:11.250
welding.

00:40:11.250 --> 00:40:13.680
We have a shortage
of skilled trades.

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:16.170
I mean, JPL needs people
to make the wheels

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:17.990
and stuff for the Mars lander.

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:21.100
Oh, there's something
really cool and really geeky

00:40:21.100 --> 00:40:23.780
about the wheels of "Curiosity."

00:40:23.780 --> 00:40:25.430
I'm gonna just let
you figure it out.

00:40:25.430 --> 00:40:27.596
And I don't know if I'm
supposed to tell you or not.

00:40:27.596 --> 00:40:32.170
But it's so geeky and anti-suit,
it's just really, really cool.

00:40:35.180 --> 00:40:37.365
But they need to have
those machinists.

00:40:37.365 --> 00:40:40.740
It's not going to
work without them.

00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:43.820
The other thing that's bad about
taking out hands-on classes

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:47.760
is we're losing resourceful
problem solving.

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:50.012
Even something as
simple with cooking.

00:40:50.012 --> 00:40:51.220
You're missing an ingredient?

00:40:51.220 --> 00:40:52.790
Can you do it with
another ingredient?

00:40:52.790 --> 00:40:54.620
'Course in the '50s,
girls were taught sewing.

00:40:54.620 --> 00:40:56.360
So I had a wonderful
toy sewing machine.

00:40:56.360 --> 00:40:57.735
I was in fourth grade.

00:40:57.735 --> 00:41:00.800
And I remember one project
where I cut the fabric wrong

00:41:00.800 --> 00:41:03.500
and I ruined it
as I got in rush.

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:06.730
Some of the things you learn
from doing hands on things.

00:41:06.730 --> 00:41:08.550
This is the stuff that saved me.

00:41:08.550 --> 00:41:11.950
These were things that were
refuges away from teasing.

00:41:11.950 --> 00:41:14.655
Kids that did the teasing were
not interested in woodworking

00:41:14.655 --> 00:41:16.800
or interested in riding horses.

00:41:16.800 --> 00:41:19.540
I was also an Estes
model rocketer.

00:41:19.540 --> 00:41:21.415
A I loved model rockets.

00:41:21.415 --> 00:41:23.345
I was in the model rocket club.

00:41:23.345 --> 00:41:25.800
And I was horrified go
on the Estes website

00:41:25.800 --> 00:41:29.440
about a month ago, and you
can buy a ready-made rocket.

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:30.580
That is disgusting!

00:41:30.580 --> 00:41:31.972
[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]

00:41:31.972 --> 00:41:34.180
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: The
whole point is to build them.

00:41:36.946 --> 00:41:39.160
And I made a few points
with the other kids

00:41:39.160 --> 00:41:41.660
when I made a rocket that
looked like our headmaster,

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:43.680
a Mr. [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:43.680 --> 00:41:46.870
And he was aerodynamically
stable and he flew.

