and they were playing
with the Brock Magiscope.

00:46:15.510 --> 00:46:17.740
And they're looking at
pond scum and leaves.

00:46:17.740 --> 00:46:21.110
And it was really cool.

00:46:21.110 --> 00:46:22.110
Just got to show people.

00:46:22.110 --> 00:46:24.526
And you guys know about this
stuff that's on the internet.

00:46:24.526 --> 00:46:27.050
But I do a lot of talks
in a lot of places,

00:46:27.050 --> 00:46:29.650
and I just want to give
people ideas of cool things

00:46:29.650 --> 00:46:32.720
that are out there.

00:46:32.720 --> 00:46:37.760
There's some evidence that kids
learning to write sometimes

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:40.010
can help them on reading.

00:46:40.010 --> 00:46:43.410
On learning reading, maybe turn
off all the bells and whistles

00:46:43.410 --> 00:46:46.400
and use the plain ebook, maybe
just with still pictures.

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:47.970
And you have them read to them.

00:46:47.970 --> 00:46:49.990
And they're learning
a story better.

00:46:49.990 --> 00:46:51.560
And again, this is refereed.

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:52.440
Scientific stuff.

00:46:52.440 --> 00:46:55.460
We're going evidence based here.

00:46:55.460 --> 00:46:57.190
Well, people need to
touch to perceive.

00:46:57.190 --> 00:46:58.575
I had a really good
time over at Pixar.

00:46:58.575 --> 00:47:00.075
They found that
sometimes they gotta

00:47:00.075 --> 00:47:04.230
get them off the computers
and get them actually drawing.

00:47:04.230 --> 00:47:06.120
And when they print
their figurines out

00:47:06.120 --> 00:47:08.240
on their 3D printer, they put
them around the computer mouse

00:47:08.240 --> 00:47:09.281
so they could touch them.

00:47:09.281 --> 00:47:11.910
You gotta touch to see.

00:47:11.910 --> 00:47:13.960
Gotta do that.

00:47:13.960 --> 00:47:14.950
Science teacher.

00:47:14.950 --> 00:47:17.160
Boy, he helped me.

00:47:17.160 --> 00:47:19.330
Well, he was a NASA
space scientist.

00:47:19.330 --> 00:47:20.460
Was he a credited teacher?

00:47:20.460 --> 00:47:21.220
No.

00:47:21.220 --> 00:47:24.300
No stupid ed courses for him.

00:47:24.300 --> 00:47:27.380
We gotta get back to doing
real things in this country.

00:47:29.940 --> 00:47:31.650
That's what we gotta do.

00:47:31.650 --> 00:47:33.610
[APPLAUSE]

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:35.610
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: One
thing a lot of employers

00:47:35.610 --> 00:47:41.440
want today is students
who know how to work.

00:47:41.440 --> 00:47:44.320
This came up in a lot of things.

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:47.300
I learned to sell
my work, not myself.

00:47:47.300 --> 00:47:49.759
Also in working with some of
the people that are different,

00:47:49.759 --> 00:47:51.675
you don't take that
employee and go, well just

00:47:51.675 --> 00:47:52.770
develop some new software.

00:47:52.770 --> 00:47:55.144
You want to say OK, I want to
make an app for the Android

00:47:55.144 --> 00:47:56.922
phone and it does
this specific thing,

00:47:56.922 --> 00:47:58.380
it uses this
language, this memory.

00:47:58.380 --> 00:48:00.440
You don't tell them
how do it, but it's

00:48:00.440 --> 00:48:02.980
got certain parameters.

00:48:02.980 --> 00:48:05.680
Then OK, that's easy to do.

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:07.810
And when mistakes
are made, the boss

00:48:07.810 --> 00:48:11.459
needs to just pull them
aside in the office quietly,

00:48:11.459 --> 00:48:13.500
no yelling and screaming,
and say, well you know,

00:48:13.500 --> 00:48:15.000
we had the project
meeting last week

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.810
and you called Jim a jerk
in front of the other five

00:48:17.810 --> 00:48:18.860
colleagues.

00:48:18.860 --> 00:48:21.350
That's not the Google
way of doing things.

00:48:21.350 --> 00:48:23.650
Just don't do that.

00:48:23.650 --> 00:48:27.430
And I learned you can
get some people that

00:48:27.430 --> 00:48:29.310
will sabotage a project
due to jealousy.

00:48:29.310 --> 00:48:31.945
That was very, very difficult
for me to deal with.

00:48:31.945 --> 00:48:33.820
And then you get other
people where they just

00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:36.730
think differently.

00:48:36.730 --> 00:48:39.280
You kind of differentiate
between the two.

00:48:39.280 --> 00:48:42.130
Well, if I in was in a plant,
on of my meat plant projects,

00:48:42.130 --> 00:48:44.485
and the plant engineer's
sitting like this--

00:48:44.485 --> 00:48:46.175
I was hired by the
manager, he didn't

00:48:46.175 --> 00:48:49.030
like this weird geek
coming on his turf.

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:51.360
I would pull him into project.

00:48:51.360 --> 00:48:54.230
And that oftentimes
stopped that.

00:48:54.230 --> 00:48:55.470
OK, tour guide.

00:48:55.470 --> 00:48:58.231
Great job for 12 year-olds.

00:48:58.231 --> 00:48:59.980
You gotta demonstrate
the correct distance

00:48:59.980 --> 00:49:01.810
to get from the visitor.

00:49:01.810 --> 00:49:03.270
Demonstrate the
correct greeting.

00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:06.810
It's just like coaching
somebody in a foreign country.

00:49:06.810 --> 00:49:08.730
And there's sensory issues.

00:49:08.730 --> 00:49:11.240
Some people just can't
stand a lot of noise,

00:49:11.240 --> 00:49:13.972
can't stand 60 cycle
fluorescent lights.

00:49:13.972 --> 00:49:15.680
You got a lot of
sensory issues, and they

00:49:15.680 --> 00:49:19.110
can vary from being very
mild to being very severe.

00:49:19.110 --> 00:49:20.870
This needs to be
researched, and how

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:23.721
to treat some of these problems.

00:49:23.721 --> 00:49:26.850
When I was a little kid,
loud sounds hurt my ears.

00:49:26.850 --> 00:49:30.030
I still absolutely hate the
vacuum toilets in airplanes.

00:49:30.030 --> 00:49:32.340
And if I'd had to deal
with those when I was five,

00:49:32.340 --> 00:49:35.610
I would have been sure I'd be
sucked out of the airplane.

00:49:35.610 --> 00:49:39.820
My visual thinking mind went
wild when I was six years old

00:49:39.820 --> 00:49:41.400
and they were
remodeling our house.

00:49:41.400 --> 00:49:44.044
They had this big circular
saw and I was afraid

00:49:44.044 --> 00:49:45.460
that maybe its
blade would come up

00:49:45.460 --> 00:49:46.668
through the floor of my room.

00:49:46.668 --> 00:49:47.860
Which was just ludicrous.

00:49:47.860 --> 00:49:49.860
But when you're
maybe six years old,

00:49:49.860 --> 00:49:51.580
it wasn't quite so ludicrous.

00:49:51.580 --> 00:49:54.760
I had trouble hearing
hard constant sounds.

00:49:54.760 --> 00:49:57.290
So my speech
teacher slowed down,

00:49:57.290 --> 00:49:59.320
enunciated the hard consonants.

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:02.320
She'd say cup, and
then shed say cuh-puh.

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:06.420
Slow down, enunciate it
so that I could hear it.

00:50:06.420 --> 00:50:09.440
Attention shifting.

00:50:09.440 --> 00:50:10.760
I have problems with this.

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:14.320
Somebody rings a
cellphone off, I orient.

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:16.610
Takes me much longer
to shift back.

00:50:16.610 --> 00:50:19.240
Attention shifting slowness.

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:20.920
Some people when
they go to read,

00:50:20.920 --> 00:50:23.070
the print will
jiggle on the page.

00:50:23.070 --> 00:50:25.620
That's probably
about 10% of students

00:50:25.620 --> 00:50:27.670
that are having some
trouble in college.

00:50:27.670 --> 00:50:29.660
Doesn't explain all autism.

00:50:29.660 --> 00:50:31.400
It doesn't explain all dyslexia.

00:50:31.400 --> 00:50:33.733
But there's something wrong
with the circuits back here.

00:50:33.733 --> 00:50:35.940
Shape, color, emotion, texture.

00:50:35.940 --> 00:50:38.110
They're not merging
together right.

00:50:38.110 --> 00:50:41.210
And sometimes they can be
fixed with a very simple thing.

00:50:41.210 --> 00:50:44.430
Like pale pink glasses,
pale lavender glasses,

00:50:44.430 --> 00:50:47.870
different print your work on
some different colored papers,

00:50:47.870 --> 00:50:50.500
maybe try different
background on colors

00:50:50.500 --> 00:50:53.090
on the computer screen,
different fonts.

00:50:53.090 --> 00:50:54.900
Now wouldn't it be
stupid to lose a job

00:50:54.900 --> 00:50:57.520
or flunk out of school
'cause you didn't do this?

00:50:57.520 --> 00:51:00.280
I'm finding one
out of 50 has got

00:51:00.280 --> 00:51:02.840
this problem in my
livestock handling class.

00:51:02.840 --> 00:51:05.770
Because they do really horrible
on my drawing assignment.

00:51:05.770 --> 00:51:06.850
They cannot draw.

00:51:06.850 --> 00:51:09.970
If I say draw this,
they're drawing.

00:51:09.970 --> 00:51:11.450
That's what they draw.

00:51:11.450 --> 00:51:13.040
They don't see it.

00:51:13.040 --> 00:51:15.390
Well, there's my head.

00:51:15.390 --> 00:51:19.590
Well, and that's all the
white matter that's inside.

00:51:19.590 --> 00:51:22.080
And the gray matter-- this
is not lining up right.

00:51:22.080 --> 00:51:23.920
Something got changed here.

00:51:23.920 --> 00:51:29.150
There should be a little space
there for the gray matter.

00:51:29.150 --> 00:51:31.740
Something got out of
sync there on that.

00:51:31.740 --> 00:51:37.120
And that's all the
circuits, the cable bundles

00:51:37.120 --> 00:51:39.236
that are the interoffice
communication.

00:51:39.236 --> 00:51:40.610
That's where you
have differences

00:51:40.610 --> 00:51:44.530
in developmental problem.

00:51:44.530 --> 00:51:47.040
Well, my fear center
was bigger than normal.

00:51:47.040 --> 00:51:50.155
Well, that's controlled now
with antidepressant medication.

00:51:50.155 --> 00:51:55.190
Little Prozac Us visual
thinkers, panic monsters.

00:51:55.190 --> 00:51:57.220
I know a lot of
visual thinkers where

00:51:57.220 --> 00:52:01.770
a little dab of Prozac in the
morning, or Lexapro or Zoloft,

00:52:01.770 --> 00:52:03.530
stops the anxiety.

00:52:03.530 --> 00:52:07.890
Then you're not getting whacked
out on drugs and alcohol.

00:52:07.890 --> 00:52:11.980
Cerebellum's smaller, so
I've got really bad balance.

00:52:11.980 --> 00:52:13.910
Simple accommodations
in the workplace.

00:52:13.910 --> 00:52:16.114
Some people have gotta
get away from the 60 cycle

00:52:16.114 --> 00:52:16.905
fluorescent lights.

00:52:16.905 --> 00:52:18.530
They need a quiet place to work.

00:52:18.530 --> 00:52:24.210
Open office plan and I gotta do
serious writing, doesn't work.

00:52:24.210 --> 00:52:25.710
The other thing
that doesn't work

00:52:25.710 --> 00:52:27.710
with people that are
on the autism spectrum

00:52:27.710 --> 00:52:29.970
is a sudden change
in work routine.

00:52:29.970 --> 00:52:32.350
They come into work
and they just go OK,

00:52:32.350 --> 00:52:34.590
we're yanking out all
the office cubicles today

00:52:34.590 --> 00:52:35.940
and we're going to move them.

00:52:35.940 --> 00:52:39.670
OK, if we're going to do
that, let's have some warning.

00:52:39.670 --> 00:52:42.100
Maybe a week at
least of warning.

00:52:42.100 --> 00:52:44.130
And I still can't
tolerate scratchy clothes.

00:52:44.130 --> 00:52:46.300
Scratchy clothes just horrible.

00:52:46.300 --> 00:52:47.710
Like sandpaper.

00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:51.630
Some cotton itches, other
cotton doesn't itch.

00:52:51.630 --> 00:52:55.070
Now the thing is it's
OK for geeks to cry.

00:52:55.070 --> 00:52:57.280
When the space
shuttle got shut down,

00:52:57.280 --> 00:52:59.800
there were a lot of people
crying on "60 Minutes."

00:52:59.800 --> 00:53:03.230
And I got thrown out
of a large girls school

00:53:03.230 --> 00:53:06.350
for throwing a book at
a girl who teased me.

00:53:06.350 --> 00:53:08.320
And when I went to
boarding school,

00:53:08.320 --> 00:53:10.250
I got in a fistfight
in the cafeteria

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:12.630
after a guy called
name some name.

00:53:12.630 --> 00:53:15.000
And they took horseback
riding away for two weeks.

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:18.620
I still had to clean the
barn, but no horseback riding.

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:20.790
And somehow I
switched to crying.

00:53:20.790 --> 00:53:22.350
It's OK for geeks to cry.

00:53:22.350 --> 00:53:24.230
That's perfectly OK.

00:53:24.230 --> 00:53:26.650
And I would go and hide
in the electrical room,

00:53:26.650 --> 00:53:30.586
because the tech companies
don't tolerate any violence.

00:53:30.586 --> 00:53:33.050
[AUDIENCE LAUGHS]

00:53:33.050 --> 00:53:34.520
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN:
I have to say

00:53:34.520 --> 00:53:38.365
that it made me chuckle to
look in the clean room at JPL

00:53:38.365 --> 00:53:43.170
and here's this big giant
Craftsman tool chest there.

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:46.360
To think that bolts on the Mars
lander were tightened by a tool

00:53:46.360 --> 00:53:48.932
kept in a Craftsman tools chest.

00:53:48.932 --> 00:53:50.390
But you better not
throw that tool,

00:53:50.390 --> 00:53:52.420
otherwise it's bye-bye job.

00:53:52.420 --> 00:53:55.530
It's that simple.

00:53:55.530 --> 00:53:57.340
It takes a village
to raise a child.

00:53:57.340 --> 00:53:59.820
We gotta figure
out how we can all

00:53:59.820 --> 00:54:02.880
work together to
make things work.

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:04.770
Because I'm seeing
too many smart kids

00:54:04.770 --> 00:54:06.790
going down the wrong road.

00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:09.370
I go to the gifted meeting,
he's going down one road.

00:54:09.370 --> 00:54:12.790
I go to the autism
meeting, and you've

00:54:12.790 --> 00:54:14.290
got one situation
where a kid that

00:54:14.290 --> 00:54:16.810
ought to be headed for
Google is put in a class

00:54:16.810 --> 00:54:18.440
with kids that don't talk.

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:19.940
Then I go to another
school system

00:54:19.940 --> 00:54:22.356
and he's headed in the right
direction really beautifully.

00:54:22.356 --> 00:54:24.520
It's very, very, very variable.

00:54:24.520 --> 00:54:27.330
But these two silos don't talk.

00:54:27.330 --> 00:54:30.190
Because if I look at the book
table for the gifted meeting

00:54:30.190 --> 00:54:31.865
and the autism
meeting, there might

00:54:31.865 --> 00:54:35.580
be a 5% overlap in the books.

00:54:35.580 --> 00:54:39.630
There should be more like
a 25% overlap in the books.

00:54:39.630 --> 00:54:42.300
They're not talking
to each other.

00:54:42.300 --> 00:54:44.570
We gotta get people together.

00:54:44.570 --> 00:54:47.910
As I say, one geek goes to
Google in Silicon Valley, maybe

00:54:47.910 --> 00:54:49.190
JPL.

00:54:49.190 --> 00:54:53.099
There's another geek that goes
to Hollywood and that stuff.

00:54:53.099 --> 00:54:54.890
And unfortunately,
there's a brilliant geek

00:54:54.890 --> 00:54:57.420
that is going to the basement
to play video games for 10

00:54:57.420 --> 00:55:00.630
hours a day and he gets
Social Security for it.

00:55:00.630 --> 00:55:03.580
That's not where
I want him going.

00:55:03.580 --> 00:55:04.080
No.

00:55:04.080 --> 00:55:06.810
We've got to reach
out, get to these kids.

00:55:06.810 --> 00:55:07.560
And you know what?

00:55:07.560 --> 00:55:09.300
We gotta hook them
in middle school.

00:55:09.300 --> 00:55:13.100
Middle school is where
we gotta hook them.

00:55:13.100 --> 00:55:17.960
And some states now are
putting skilled trades back in.

00:55:17.960 --> 00:55:21.710
OK, I think that finishes
up what I have to say.

00:55:21.710 --> 00:55:24.210
But I've got time for questions.

00:55:24.210 --> 00:55:26.152
Always like to do
some questions.

00:55:26.152 --> 00:55:35.992
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:35.992 --> 00:55:38.815
AUDIENCE: I'm curious over
the course of your career,

00:55:38.815 --> 00:55:40.440
you've shared a lot
of the insights you

00:55:40.440 --> 00:55:42.530
had about the experience of
animals in slaughterhouses.

00:55:42.530 --> 00:55:44.113
I'm curious about
what kinds of things

00:55:44.113 --> 00:55:45.684
you learned over your career.

00:55:45.684 --> 00:55:47.100
Like where maybe
you can look back

00:55:47.100 --> 00:55:48.974
on some of your earlier
work and see oh, this

00:55:48.974 --> 00:55:50.937
is what I understand so
much more deeply now?

00:55:50.937 --> 00:55:53.020
DR. TEMPLE GRANDIN: Well,
there's a lot of things,

00:55:53.020 --> 00:55:55.514
I mean, for one
thing in the '70s,

00:55:55.514 --> 00:55:57.680
my first professional group
was the American Society

00:55:57.680 --> 00:55:59.221
of Agricultural
Engineering I thought

00:55:59.221 --> 00:56:00.880
I could fix the world
with engineering.

00:56:00.880 --> 00:56:03.060
I absolutely believed
that everything

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:05.340
could be fixed with engineering.

00:56:05.340 --> 00:56:09.290
I now realize only half of it
can be fixed with engineering.

00:56:09.290 --> 00:56:11.980
And I had a major
equipment failure,

00:56:11.980 --> 00:56:13.760
which was a real epiphany.

00:56:13.760 --> 00:56:18.080
I was hired by a company in
1980 to run the old slaughter

00:56:18.080 --> 00:56:18.760
plants.

00:56:18.760 --> 00:56:20.670
The pigs had to walk
up to the third floor

00:56:20.670 --> 00:56:22.185
in the real old plants.

00:56:22.185 --> 00:56:24.060
And they wanted me to
build a conveyor system

00:56:24.060 --> 00:56:27.340
to put in the floor of the chute
to take the pigs up this ramp.

00:56:27.340 --> 00:56:30.880
And I said, I'll design that.

00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:34.590
Well, the problem is it flipped
all the pigs over backwards.

00:56:34.590 --> 00:56:36.810
And it did not work and
we had to tear it out.

00:56:36.810 --> 00:56:39.210
But then I started
realizing now why

00:56:39.210 --> 00:56:44.300
are some pigs not capable
of walking up this ramp?

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:46.710
Well, I start getting
the ID numbers off

00:56:46.710 --> 00:56:48.770
of the different
pigs and I found out

00:56:48.770 --> 00:56:51.650
that all the pigs that a
problem came from one farm.

00:56:51.650 --> 00:56:54.930
And they had a genetic problem
called spraddle leg, where

00:56:54.930 --> 00:56:58.190
the hips are very, very weak.

00:56:58.190 --> 00:57:00.830
What I should have done, by
trying to make a conveyor,

00:57:00.830 --> 00:57:02.970
that was treating a
symptom of a problem.

00:57:02.970 --> 00:57:05.680
We should have gone
back to the source.

00:57:05.680 --> 00:57:08.440
For a fraction of the cost
of this mess that we had,

00:57:08.440 --> 00:57:12.560
we could have bought that
farm new boars-- five or six

00:57:12.560 --> 00:57:14.385
new boars is all it
would have taken,

00:57:14.385 --> 00:57:17.360
just a few thousand
dollars-- and gotten rid

00:57:17.360 --> 00:57:18.360
of that genetic problem.

00:57:18.360 --> 00:57:19.905
Would have solved it.

00:57:19.905 --> 00:57:21.530
One thing I learned
from that is you've

00:57:21.530 --> 00:57:24.070
got the treat problem
at its source,

00:57:24.070 --> 00:57:26.640
rather than treating a
symptom of a problem.

00:57:26.640 --> 00:57:29.140
Now I went into about a six
month depression over that.

00:57:29.140 --> 00:57:31.180
That was not fun.

00:57:31.180 --> 00:57:34.845
But I learned a really
important lesson from that.

00:57:34.845 --> 00:57:36.376
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

